
[1]aversion

   AVER'SION, n. [L. averto.]

   1. Opposition or repugnance of mind; dislike; disinclination;
   reluctance; hatred. Usually this word expresses moderate hatred, or
   opposition of mind, not amounting to abhorrence or detestation. It
   ought generally to be followed by to before the object. [See averse.]
   Sometimes it admits of for.

   A freeholder is bred with an aversion to subjection.

   2. Opposition or contrariety of nature; applied to inanimate
   substances.

   Magnesia, notwithstanding this aversion to solution, forms a kind of
   paste with water.

   3. The cause of dislike.

   Pain their aversion, pleasure their desire.
